@TheVeryVery It can actually see the fire truck across the road and know what it is. It does not need a lot of humans to report that the right lane is closed; it can see that for itself. While it didn't warn everybody behind me that it saw the closure, it needs to do that.

That is the power of a neural network—it does not need to have a human in the loop at all. Once a human takes a picture and posts it to X, that data feeds back into the system to be validated and verified by the AI itself. This stuff is solvable, even when it comes to fake reporting. I've already seen systems in labs that can tell whether something is fake or true. 

We are going to see new systems turn on next year that will validate all sorts of news reports, police reports, and other data points. They will start putting together a complete picture of what the hell is going on—in this case, perhaps a fire or something else that closed down a whole neighborhood.

@aramp0x Then you and I are only disagreeing in what “vibe-coding” means.

To me, vibe-coding is asking the agent for what you want and shipping a large portion of the code it generates.

I can have a product 90% written by me, and still vibe-code 3% of it.

