@theJoshMeister In America at least, if you're on the public street, you have no expectation of privacy. You can be broadcast at any time for any reason.

This is a very clear First Amendment law. I studied it in college and I used it many times as a journalist. If you're in the street, I can take a picture of you and put it on the front page of the newspaper with all of that information, and there's nothing you can do about it. 

If you try to do something about it, you're breaking the First Amendment right for me to publish information about an actual news event, which is the case under discussion here.

@Art_If_Ficial @theJoshMeister @Tesla_AI @Tesla Me too. It's a bit of a difficult problem, but they do need several new systems turned on to warn drivers of closed streets. 

Even if you can't reroute completely around all the closures, as soon as a Tesla sees a closed street, it should appear on the map to show, "Hey, closed street here." Very quickly, even a human driver in a Tesla should be able to reroute around the blockage. 

Certainly, as soon as X posts about it, the system should understand it—but we were actually ahead of the X posts.

